article.description: Allen Iverson scored 31 points to lead the Philadelphia 76ers a 94-83 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers on Monday night.
article.headline: Philly snaps two-game skid
article.linkText: Iverson scores 31 to lead 76ers over Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Allen Iverson is more concerned with winning than individual achievements this early in the season. Iverson scored 31 points to give the Philadelphia 76ers a 94-83 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers on Monday night. "It's just important because it was a win, there's not a whole bunch to it," he said. "After losing two in a row, nothing could be more important than this one." Iverson got some help from Glenn Robinson, who made his season debut after missing the first three games because of an NBA-imposed suspension after a domestic assault and battery conviction. Robinson was acquired from Atlanta in a four-team deal in August, and complemented Iverson with 15 points as the Sixers overcame an early deficit to lead by as many as 18. "It felt good. I think it opened Allen's game up a little bit," Robinson said of his return. "They couldn't swarm on him." The win snapped a two-game losing streak on the West Coast for the 76ers. Rasheed Wallace had 22 points and seven rebounds to lead the Blazers. Philadelphia had lost two straight on the road, against Sacramento and Golden State, after defeating Miami in its season-opener at home. Zach Randolph added 11 points and 11 rebounds for the Blazers, who lost their opener at Utah then beat Cleveland at home Saturday. Portland shot just 39.2 percent from the floor, and struggled with free throws, shooting 18-of-28 from the line. After a series of missed shots, coach Maurice Cheeks retreated to the bench and buried his face in his hands. "What can you say about that game?" Cheeks said. "Obviously they played better than us." The Blazers led by as many as nine early in the game, but Philadelphia went ahead 25-24 on Iverson's fadeaway jumper. Both teams wrestled back and forth, but Iverson but the 76ers ahead 41-34 with a 3-pointer with 4:57 left in the first half. Iverson, who said a sprained left shoulder wasn't bothering him, had piled up 21 points by the first half, including a foul shot that put the 76ers ahead 50-41 at halftime. "You are not going to shut that guy down," Cheeks said. Robinson's fast-break layup put the Sixers up 60-48 and the Blazers could only get as close as eight the rest of the way. Iverson is comfortable at the Rose Garden, where he scored 36 in an 88-60 victory last March. He's a fan favorite, too, earning cheers as the starting lineups were announced. "We took all the negative out of the last two games and put some good into this one," Iverson said.

Game notes
Guard Derek Anderson who missed the Blazers' first two games because of back spasms, appeared for the first time this season in the fourth quarter. Anderson was a starter last season. ... Cheeks was a four-time All-Star for the 76ers and helped the team win the NBA title in 1983. ... The 76ers beat the Trail Blazers in both of their meetings last season. ... The Blazers honored longtime broadcaster Bill Schonely with a halftime ceremony. A banner honoring Schonely was raised to the rafters of the Rose Garden and he was treated to a standing ovation.
